# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cambrian
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] In geology, **accretion** is a process by which material is added to a tectonic plate at a subduction zone, frequently on the edge of existing continental landmasses.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] The added material may be sediment, volcanic arcs, seamounts, oceanic crust or other igneous features.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Accretion involves the addition of material to a tectonic plate via subduction, the process by which one plate is forced under the other when two plates collide.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] The plate which is being forced down, the subducted plate, is pushed against the upper, over-riding plate.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Sediment on the ocean floor of the subducting plate is often scraped off as the plate descends.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] This accumulated material is called an accretionary wedge (or accretionary prism), which is pushed against and attaches to the upper plate.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] In addition to accumulated ocean sediments, volcanic island arcs or seamounts present on the subducting plate may be amalgamated onto existing continental crust on the upper plate, increasing the continental landmass.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Continental crust differs significantly from oceanic crust.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Oceanic crust is primarily composed of basaltic rocks, which have a higher density than the rocks making up the majority of continental crust.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Island arcs and other volcanic rocks are also lower in density than the oceanic crust, and are therefore not easily subducted along with the oceanic crust that surrounds them.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Instead, these less-dense bits of crust will collide with existing continental crust on the upper plate once the oceanic crust separating them is completely subducted.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] Most continents are composed of multiple accreted "terranes", pieces of low-density continental crust with different origins.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] For example, North America is made up of multiple accreted terranes that collided with the Laurentian proto-continent, such as the Proterozoic Yavapai, Mazatzal, and Grenville Province Terranes.
[src:cambrian/accretion-geology] These examples of accreted terranes also all include accretionary wedges.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] An **accretionary wedge** or **accretionary prism** forms from sediments accreted onto the non-subducting tectonic plate at a convergent plate boundary.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Most of the material in the accretionary wedge consists of marine sediments scraped off from the downgoing slab of oceanic crust, but in some cases the wedge includes the erosional products of volcanic island arcs formed on the overriding plate.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] An **accretionary complex** is a current (in modern use) or former accretionary wedge.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Accretionary complexes are typically made up of a mix of turbidites of terrestrial material, basalts from the ocean floor, and pelagic and hemipelagic sediments.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] For example, most of the geological basement of Japan is made up of accretionary complexes.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Accretionary wedges and accreted terranes are not equivalent to tectonic plates, but rather are associated with tectonic plates and accrete as a result of tectonic collision.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Elevated regions within the ocean basins such as linear island chains, ocean ridges, and small crustal fragments (such as Madagascar or Japan), known as terranes, are transported toward the subduction zone and accreted to the continental margin.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Since the Late Devonian and Early Carboniferous periods, some 360 million years ago, subduction beneath the western margin of North America has resulted in several collisions with terranes, each producing a mountain-building event.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The piecemeal addition of these accreted terranes has added an average of 600 km (370 mi) in width along the western margin of the North American continent.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The topographic expression of the accretionary wedge forms a lip, which may dam basins of accumulated materials that, otherwise, would be transported into the trench from the overriding plate.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Accretionary wedges are the home of mélange, intensely deformed packages of rocks that lack coherent internal layering and coherent internal order.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The internal structure of an accretionary wedge is similar to that found in a thin-skinned foreland thrust belt.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] A series of thrusts verging towards the trench are formed with the youngest most outboard structures progressively uplifting the older more inboard thrusts.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The shape of the wedge is determined by how readily the wedge will fail along its basal decollement and in its interior; this is highly sensitive to pore fluid pressure.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] This failure will result in a mature wedge that has an equilibrium triangular cross-sectional shape of a critical taper.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Once the wedge reaches a critical taper, it will maintain that geometry and grow only into a larger similar triangle.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The small sections of oceanic crust that are thrust over the overriding plate are said to be obducted.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Where this occurs, rare slices of ocean crust, known as ophiolites, are preserved on land.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] They provide a valuable natural laboratory for studying the composition and character of the oceanic crust and the mechanisms of their emplacement and preservation on land.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] A classic example is the Coast Range ophiolite of California, which is one of the most extensive ophiolite terranes in North America.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] This oceanic crust likely formed during the middle Jurassic Period, roughly 170 million years ago, in an extensional regime within either a back-arc or a forearc basin.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] It was later accreted to the continental margin of Laurasia.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Longitudinal sedimentary tapering of pre-orogenic sediments correlates strongly with curvature of the submarine frontal accretionary belt in the South China Sea margin, suggesting that pre-orogenic sediment thickness is the major control on the geometry of frontal structures.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The preexisting South China Sea slope that lies obliquely in front of the advancing accretionary wedge has impeded the advancing of frontal folds resulting in a successive termination of folds against and along strike of the South China Sea slope.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The existence of the South China Sea slope also leads the strike of impinging folds with NNW-trend to turn more sharply to a NE-strike, parallel to strike of the South China Sea slope.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Analysis shows that the pre-orogenic mechanical/crustal heterogeneities and seafloor morphology exert strong controls on the thrust-belt development in the incipient Taiwan arc-continent collision zone.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] In accretionary wedges, seismicity activating superimposed thrusts may drive methane and oil upraising from the upper crust.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Mechanical models that treat accretionary complexes as critically tapered wedges of sediment demonstrate that pore pressure controls their taper angle by modifying basal and internal shear strength.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Results from some studies show that pore pressure in accretionary wedges can be viewed as a dynamically maintained response to factors which drive pore pressure (source terms) and those that limit flow (permeability and drainage path length).
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Sediment permeability and incoming sediment thickness are the most important factors, whereas fault permeability and the partitioning of sediment have a small effect.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] In one such study, it was found that as sediment permeability is increased, pore pressure decreases from near-lithostatic to hydrostatic values and allows stable taper angles to increase from ~2.5° to 8°–12.5°.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] With increased sediment thickness (from 100–8,000 m (330–26,250 ft)), increased pore pressure drives a decrease in stable taper angle from 8.4°–12.5° to <2.5–5°.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] In general, low-permeability and thick incoming sediment sustain high pore pressures consistent with shallowly tapered geometry, whereas high-permeability and thin incoming sediment should result in steep geometry.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Observations from active margins also indicate a strong trend of decreasing taper angle (from >15° to <4°) with increased sediment thickness (from <1 to 7 km).
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Rapid tectonic loading of wet sediment in accretionary wedges is likely to cause the fluid pressure to rise until it is sufficient to cause dilatant fracturing.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Dewatering of sediment that has been underthrust and accreted beneath the wedge can produce a large steady supply of such highly overpressured fluid.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Dilatant fracturing will create escape routes, so the fluid pressure is likely to be buffered at the value required for the transition between shear and oblique tensile (dilatant) fracture, which is slightly in excess of the load pressure if the maximum compression is nearly horizontal.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] This in turn buffers the strength of the wedge at the cohesive strength, which is not pressure-dependent, and will not vary greatly throughout the wedge.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Near the wedge front the strength is likely to be that of the cohesion on existing thrust faults in the wedge.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] The shear resistance on the base of the wedge will also be fairly constant and related to the cohesive strength of the weak sediment layer that acts as the basal detachment.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] These assumptions allow the application of a simple plastic continuum model, which successfully predicts the observed gently convex taper of accretionary wedges.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Pelayo and Weins have postulated that some tsunami events have resulted from rupture through the sedimentary rock along the basal decollement of an accretionary wedge.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Backthrusting of the rear of the accretionary wedge, arcward over the rocks of the forearc basin, is a common aspect of accretionary tectonics.
[src:cambrian/accretionary-wedge] Backthrusting may be favored where relief is high between the crest of the wedge and the surface of the forearc basin because the relief must be supported by shear stress along the backthrust.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Acritarchs were originally defined as non-acid soluble (i.e. non-carbonate, non-siliceous) organic-walled microfossils consisting of a central cavity, and whose biological affinities cannot be determined with certainty.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Most commonly they are composed of thermally altered acid-insoluble carbon compounds (kerogen).
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Acritarchs may include the remains of a wide range of quite different kinds of organisms—ranging from the egg cases of small metazoans to resting cysts of many kinds of chlorophyta (green algae).
[src:cambrian/acritarch] It is likely that most acritarch species from the Paleozoic represent various stages of the life cycle of algae that were ancestral to the dinoflagellates.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] The nature of the organisms associated with Precambrian acritarchs is generally not well understood, though many are probably related to unicellular marine algae.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] In theory, when the biological source (taxon) of an acritarch does become known, that particular microfossil is removed from the acritarchs and classified with its proper group.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] While the classification of acritarchs into form genera is entirely artificial, it is not without merit, as the form taxa show traits similar to those of genuine taxa—for example an 'explosion' in the Cambrian and a mass extinction at the end of the Permian.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] The informal group Acritarcha Evitt 1963 was originally divided into these Subgroups: Acanthomorphitae, Polygonomorphitae, Prismatomorphitae, Oömorphitae, Netromorphitae, Dinetromorphitae, Stephanomorphitae, Pteromorphitae, Herkomorphitae, Platymorphitae, Sphaeromorphitae, and Disphaeromorphitae.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] In the end, it may well be, as Moczydłowska et al. suggested in 2011, that many acritarchs will, in fact, turn out to be algae.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Acritarchs are found in sedimentary rocks from the present back into the Archean.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] They are typically isolated from siliciclastic sedimentary rocks using hydrofluoric acid but are occasionally extracted from carbonate-rich rocks.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] They are excellent candidates for index fossils used for dating rock formations in the Paleozoic Era and when other fossils are not available.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Because most acritarchs are thought to be marine (pre-Triassic), they are also useful for palaeoenvironmental interpretation.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] The Archean and earliest Proterozoic microfossils termed "acritarchs" may actually be prokaryotes.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] The earliest eukaryotic acritarchs known (as of 2020) are from between 1950 and 2150 million years ago.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] At about 1 billion years ago the organisms responsible for acritarchs started to increase in abundance, diversity, size, complexity of shape, and especially, the size and number of spines.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Their populations crashed during periods of extensive worldwide glaciations that covered the majority of the planet, but they proliferated in the Cambrian explosion and reached their highest diversity in the Paleozoic.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] The increased spininess 1000 million years ago possibly resulted from the need for defense against predators, especially predators large enough to swallow them or tear them apart.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Other groups of small organisms from the Neoproterozoic era also show signs of anti-predator defenses.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Further evidence that acritarchs were subject to herbivory around this time comes from a consideration of taxon longevity.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Approximately 1,000 million years ago, species longevity fell sharply, suggesting that predation pressure, probably by protist herbivores, became an important factor.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] Predation would have kept populations in check, meaning that some nutrients were left unused, and new niches were available for new species to occupy.
[src:cambrian/acritarch] There are over 900 described genera; the following is a partial list, from Fossilid.info.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Though he had guided the young Charles Darwin in his early study of geology and continued to be on friendly terms, Sedgwick was an opponent of Darwin's theory of evolution by means of natural selection.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Sedgwick was born in Dent, Yorkshire, the third child of an Anglican vicar.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He was educated at Sedbergh School and Trinity College, Cambridge.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He studied mathematics and theology, and obtained his BA (5th Wrangler) from the University of Cambridge in 1808 and his MA in 1811.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] On 20 July 1817 he was ordained a deacon, then a year later he was ordained as a priest.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] His academic mentors at Cambridge were Thomas Jones and John Dawson.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He became a Fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge and Woodwardian Professor of Geology at Cambridge from 1818, holding the chair until his death in 1873.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] His biography in the Cambridge Alumni database says that upon his acceptance of the position, Sedgwick had no working knowledge of geology.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] An 1851 portrait of Sedgwick by William Boxall hangs in Trinity's collection.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Sedgwick studied the geology of the British Isles and Europe.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He founded the system for the classification of Cambrian rocks and with Roderick Murchison worked out the order of the Carboniferous and underlying Devonian strata.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] These studies were mostly carried out in the 1830s.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The investigations into the Devonian meant that Sedgwick was involved with Murchison in a vigorous debate with Henry De la Beche, in what became known as the great Devonian controversy.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He also employed John William Salter for a short time in arranging the fossils in the Woodwardian Museum at Cambridge, and whom accompanied the professor on several geological expeditions (1842–1845) into Wales.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] John Ruthven, with whom Sedgwick has a room at Kendal museum co-named after him, also frequently accompanied Sedgwick in Wales and beyond.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Sedgwick investigated the phenomena of metamorphism and concretion, and was the first to distinguish clearly between stratification, jointing, and slaty cleavage.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He was elected to Fellow of the Royal Society on 1 February 1821.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In 1844, he was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He was president of the Geological Society of London.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The Church of England, by no means a fundamentalist or evangelical church, encloses a wide range of beliefs.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] During Sedgwick's life there developed something of a chasm between the conservative high church believers and the liberal wing.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] After simmering for some years, the publication of *Essays and Reviews* by liberal churchmen in 1860 pinpointed the differences.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In all this, Sedgwick, whose science and faith were intertwined in a natural theology, was definitely on the conservative side, and extremely outspoken about it.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] No opinion can be heretical, but that which is not true....
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Conflicting falsehoods we can comprehend; but truths can never war against each other.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] I affirm, therefore, that we have nothing to fear from the results of our enquiries, provided they be followed in the laborious but secure road of honest induction.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Sedgwick's subsequent investigations and discussions with continental geologists persuaded him that this was problematic.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In early 1827, after spending several weeks in Paris, he visited geological features in the Scottish Highlands with Roderick Murchison.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He later wrote "If I have been converted in part from the diluvian theory...it was...by my own gradual improved experience, and by communicating with those about me.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Perhaps I may date my change of mind (at least in part) from our journey in the Highlands, where there are so many indications of local diluvial operations....
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Humboldt ridiculed [the doctrine] beyond measure when I met him in Paris.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He strongly believed that species of organisms originated in a succession of Divine creative acts throughout the long expanse of history.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Any form of development that denied a direct creative action smacked as materialistic and amoral.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] For Sedgwick, moral truths (the obtainment of which separates man from beast) were to be distinguished from physical truths, and to combine these or blur them together could only lead to disastrous consequences.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In fact, one's own hope for immortality may ultimately rest on it.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] They show "bigotry and ignorance," of nature's laws and natural phenomena.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Henry Cole then responded in 1834 in a 136-page "letter," *Popular Geology Subversive of Divine Revelation*.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He referred to Sedgwick's ideas as "unscriptural and anti-Christian," "scripture-defying", "revelation-subverting," and "baseless speculations and self-contradictions," which were "impious and infidel".
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] While he became increasingly Evangelical with age, he strongly supported advances in geology against conservative churchmen.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] At the September 1844 British Association for the Advancement of Science meeting at York he achieved national celebrity for his reply defending modern geology against an attack by the Dean of York, the Reverend William Cockburn, who described it as unscriptural.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] When Robert Chambers anonymously published his own theory of universal evolutionism as his "development hypothesis" in the book *Vestiges of the Natural History of Creation* published in October 1844 to immediate popular success, Sedgwick's many friends urged him to respond.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Like other eminent scientists he initially ignored the book, but the subject kept recurring and he then read it carefully and made a withering attack on the book in the July 1845 edition of the *Edinburgh Review*.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] *Vestiges* "comes before [its readers] with a bright, polished, and many-coloured surface, and the serpent coils a false philosophy, and asks them to stretch out their hands and pluck the forbidden fruit", he wrote in his review.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Accepting the arguments in *Vestiges* was akin to falling from grace and away from God's favour.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He lashed out at the book in a letter to Charles Lyell, bemoaning the consequences of its conclusions.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Charles Darwin was one of his geology students in 1831, and accompanied him on a field trip to Wales that summer.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The two kept up a correspondence while Darwin was on the *Beagle* expedition, and afterwards.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] However, Sedgwick never accepted the case for evolution made in *On the Origin of Species* in 1859 any more than he did that in *Vestiges* in 1844.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] If I did not think you a good tempered & truth loving man I should not tell you that...
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] I have read your book with more pain than pleasure.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] s locomotive that was to sail with us to the Moon.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Many of your wide conclusions are based upon assumptions which can neither be proved nor disproved.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Why then express them in the language & arrangements of philosophical induction?
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] but a secondary consequence of supposed, or known, primary facts.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Development is a better word because more close to the cause of the fact.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] I call (in the abstract) causation the will of God: & I can prove that He acts for the good of His creatures.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He emphasised his distinction between the moral and physical aspects of life, "There is a moral or metaphysical part of nature as well as a physical.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] A man who denies this is deep in the mire of folly".
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] If humanity broke this distinction it "would suffer a damage that might brutalize it—& sink the human race into a lower grade of degradation than any into which it has fallen since its written records tell us of its history".
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In a letter to another correspondent, Sedgwick was even harsher on Darwin's book, calling it "*utterly false*" and writing that "It repudiates all reasoning from final causes; and seems to shut the door on any view (however feeble) of the God of Nature as manifested in His works.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] From first to last it is a dish of rank materialism cleverly cooked and served up".
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Despite this difference of opinion, the two men remained friendly until Sedgwick's death.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In contrast to Sedgwick, liberal church members (who included biologists such as George Rolleston, William Henry Flower and William Kitchen Parker) were usually comfortable with evolution.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] A liberal Whig in politics, Sedgwick had long been a passionate supporter of abolition.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In a letter to Bishop Wilberforce, dated July 16, 1848, Sedgwick wrote of signing a petition against the slave trade while he was a child—the first "political act of [his] life"—after his father had shown him "ugly pictures of the horrors of slavery".
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] However, although Sedgwick did nothing to further slavery, he was arguably a beneficiary of it through his links with the Sill family, who were his neighbours in Yorkshire.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The Sills owned slaves in Jamaica and brought at least one back home to Dentdale.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Ann Sill, described on her memorial in Dent church as "last survivor of the aforesaid family", owned slaves in 1834 when the abolition of slavery in the British Empire was put into effect.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] She claimed compensation, but died in 1835 before it was awarded.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The money went to the co-trustees of her will, one of whom was Sedgwick.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Details are given in the database of the Centre for the Study of the Legacies of British Slavery.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He was awarded half of £3,783 in compensation for 174 slaves.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] This was to be passed on to beneficiaries of the will (of which he was one).
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] He was one of 46,000 people paid compensation by the British government following the abolition of slavery.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] In 1865, the University of Cambridge received from A.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Van Sittart the sum of 500 pounds sterling "for the purpose of encouraging the study of geology among the resident members of the university, and in honour of the Rev.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Thus was founded the Sedgwick Prize to be given every third year for the best essay on some geological subject.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The first Sedgwick Prize was awarded in 1873 and has continued into the 21st century.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The Sedgwick Club, the oldest student-run geological society in the world, was set up in honour of him in 1880.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] On the death of Sedgwick it was decided that his memorial should take the form of a new and larger museum.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] There was brief, later discarded, talk of opening a Sedgwick youth summer programme.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Hitherto the geological collections had been placed in the Woodwardian Museum in Cockerell's Building.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Hughes (successor to Sedgwick) the new building, termed the Sedgwick Museum, was completed and opened in 1903.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] To celebrate the bicentenary of Sedgwick's birth a geological trail was created near Dent, the village where he was born and developed his passion for geology (amongst other things).
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] The Sedgwick Trail follows the River Clough, highlighting rock features and exploring the Dent Fault.
[src:cambrian/adam-sedgwick] Mount Sedgwick in British Columbia, Canada, was officially named after him in 1951.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The **age of Earth** is estimated to be 4.54 ± 0.05 billion years.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This age corresponds to the final stages of Earth's accretion and planetary differentiation during the early Hadean eon.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Estimates are based on radiometric dating of meteoritic material—the ages of which are approached by those of the oldest-known terrestrial material and lunar samples—and accretion models consistent with observations of planet formation in protoplanetary disks.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Following the development of radiometric dating in the early 20th century, measurements of lead in uranium-rich minerals showed that some were in excess of a billion years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The oldest such minerals analyzed to date, small crystals of zircon from the Jack Hills of Western Australia, are at least 4.404 billion years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Calcium–aluminium-rich inclusions (CAIs), the oldest known solid matter that formed within the Solar System, are 4.5673 ± 0.00016 billion years old, giving a lower limit for the age of the Solar System.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] It is inferred that the accretion of Earth began soon after the formation of CAIs.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Because the duration of this accretion process is not yet adequately constrained—predictions from different models range from around 30 to 100 million years—the difference between the age of Earth and of the oldest rocks is difficult to determine.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] It can also be difficult to determine the exact age of the oldest rocks on Earth, exposed at the surface, as they are aggregates of minerals of possibly different ages.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Studies of strata—the layering of rocks and soil—gave naturalists an appreciation that Earth may have been through many changes during its existence.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] These layers often contained fossilized remains of unknown creatures, leading some to interpret a progression of organisms from layer to layer.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Nicolas Steno in the 17th century was one of the first naturalists to appreciate the connection between fossil remains and strata.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] His observations led him to formulate important stratigraphic concepts (i.e., the "law of superposition" and the "principle of original horizontality").
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In the 1790s, William Smith hypothesized that if two layers of rock at widely differing locations contained similar fossils, then it was very plausible that the layers were the same age.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Smith's nephew and student, John Phillips, later calculated by such means that Earth was about 96 million years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In the mid-18th century, the naturalist Mikhail Lomonosov suggested that Earth had been created separately from, and several hundred thousand years before, the rest of the universe.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Lomonosov's ideas were mostly speculative.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1779 the Comte de Buffon tried to obtain a value for the age of Earth using an experiment: he created a small globe that resembled Earth in composition and then measured its rate of cooling.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This led him to estimate that the Earth was 74,832 years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Other naturalists used these hypotheses to construct a history of Earth, though their timelines were inexact as they did not know how long it took to lay down stratigraphic layers.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1830, geologist Charles Lyell, developing ideas found in James Hutton's works, popularized the concept that the features of Earth were in perpetual change, eroding and reforming continuously, and the rate of this change was roughly constant.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This was a challenge to the traditional view, which saw the history of Earth as dominated by intermittent catastrophes.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Many naturalists were influenced by Lyell to become "uniformitarians" who believed that changes were constant and uniform.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1862, the physicist William Thomson, 1st Baron Kelvin published calculations that fixed the age of Earth at between 20 million and 400 million years.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] He assumed that Earth had formed as a completely molten object, and determined the amount of time it would take for the near-surface temperature gradient to decrease to its present value.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] His calculations did not account for heat produced via radioactive decay (a then unknown process) or, more significantly, convection inside Earth, which allows the temperature in the upper mantle to remain high much longer, maintaining a high thermal gradient in the crust much longer.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Even more constraining were Thomson's estimates of the age of the Sun, which were based on estimates of its thermal output and a theory that the Sun obtains its energy from gravitational collapse; Thomson estimated that the Sun is about 20 million years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Geologists such as Lyell had difficulty accepting such a short age for Earth.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] For biologists, even 100 million years seemed much too short to be plausible.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In Charles Darwin's theory of evolution, the process of random heritable variation with cumulative selection requires great durations of time, and Darwin stated that Thomson's estimates did not appear to provide enough time.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] According to modern biology, the total evolutionary history from the beginning of life to today has taken place since 3.5 to 3.8 billion years ago, the amount of time which passed since the last universal ancestor of all living organisms as shown by geological dating.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In a lecture in 1869, Darwin's great advocate, Thomas Henry Huxley, attacked Thomson's calculations, suggesting they appeared precise in themselves but were based on faulty assumptions.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Their values were consistent with Thomson's calculations.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] However, they assumed that the Sun was only glowing from the heat of its gravitational contraction.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The process of solar nuclear fusion was not yet known to science.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1892, Thomson was ennobled as Lord Kelvin in appreciation of his many scientific accomplishments.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1895 John Perry challenged Kelvin's figure on the basis of his assumptions on conductivity, and Oliver Heaviside entered the dialogue, considering it "a vehicle to display the ability of his operator method to solve problems of astonishing complexity." Other scientists backed up Kelvin's figures.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Darwin, proposed that Earth and Moon had broken apart in their early days when they were both molten.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] He calculated the amount of time it would have taken for tidal friction to give Earth its current 24-hour day.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] His value of 56 million years was additional evidence that Thomson was on the right track.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The last estimate Kelvin gave, in 1897, was: "that it was more than 20 and less than 40 million year old, and probably much nearer 20 than 40".
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1899 and 1900, John Joly calculated the rate at which the oceans should have accumulated salt from erosion processes and determined that the oceans were about 80 to 100 million years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] By their chemical nature, rock minerals contain certain elements and not others; but in rocks containing radioactive isotopes, the process of radioactive decay generates exotic elements over time.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] By measuring the concentration of the stable end product of the decay, coupled with knowledge of the half life and initial concentration of the decaying element, the age of the rock can be calculated.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Typical radioactive end products are argon from decay of potassium-40, and lead from decay of uranium and thorium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] If the rock becomes molten, as happens in Earth's mantle, such nonradioactive end products typically escape or are redistributed.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Thus the age of the oldest terrestrial rock gives a minimum for the age of Earth, assuming that no rock has been intact for longer than Earth itself.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The discovery of radioactivity introduced another factor in the calculation.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] After Henri Becquerel's initial discovery in 1896, Marie and Pierre Curie discovered the radioactive elements polonium and radium in 1898; and in 1903, Pierre Curie and Albert Laborde announced that radium produces enough heat to melt its own weight in ice in less than an hour.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Geologists quickly realized that this upset the assumptions underlying most calculations of the age of Earth.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] These had assumed that the original heat of Earth and the Sun had dissipated steadily into space, but radioactive decay meant that this heat had been continually replenished.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] George Darwin and John Joly were the first to point this out, in 1903.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Radioactivity, which had overthrown the old calculations, yielded a bonus by providing a basis for new calculations, in the form of radiometric dating.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Ernest Rutherford and Frederick Soddy jointly had continued their work on radioactive materials and concluded that radioactivity was caused by a spontaneous transmutation of atomic elements.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In radioactive decay, an element breaks down into another, lighter element, releasing alpha, beta, or gamma radiation in the process.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] They also determined that a particular isotope of a radioactive element decays into another element at a distinctive rate.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This rate is given in terms of a "half-life", or the amount of time it takes half of a mass of that radioactive material to break down into its "decay product".
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Some radioactive materials have short half-lives; some have long half-lives.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Uranium and thorium have long half-lives and so persist in Earth's crust, but radioactive elements with short half-lives have generally disappeared.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This suggested that it might be possible to measure the age of Earth by determining the relative proportions of radioactive materials in geological samples.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In reality, radioactive elements do not always decay into nonradioactive ("stable") elements directly, instead, decaying into other radioactive elements that have their own half-lives and so on, until they reach a stable element.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] These "decay chains", such as the uranium-radium and thorium series, were known within a few years of the discovery of radioactivity and provided a basis for constructing techniques of radiometric dating.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The pioneers of radioactivity were chemist Bertram B.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood had conducted studies of radioactive materials as a consultant, and when Rutherford lectured at Yale in 1904, Boltwood was inspired to describe the relationships between elements in various decay series.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Late in 1904, Rutherford took the first step toward radiometric dating by suggesting that the alpha particles released by radioactive decay could be trapped in a rocky material as helium atoms.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] At the time, Rutherford was only guessing at the relationship between alpha particles and helium atoms, but he would prove the connection four years later.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Soddy and Sir William Ramsay had just determined the rate at which radium produces alpha particles, and Rutherford proposed that he could determine the age of a rock sample by measuring its concentration of helium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] He dated a rock in his possession to an age of 40 million years by this technique.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Rutherford assumed that the rate of decay of radium as determined by Ramsay and Soddy was accurate and that helium did not escape from the sample over time.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Rutherford's scheme was inaccurate, but it was a useful first step.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood focused on the end products of decay series.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In 1905, he suggested that lead was the final stable product of the decay of radium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] It was already known that radium was an intermediate product of the decay of uranium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Rutherford joined in, outlining a decay process in which radium emitted five alpha particles through various intermediate products to end up with lead, and speculated that the radium–lead decay chain could be used to date rock samples.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood did the legwork and by the end of 1905 had provided dates for 26 separate rock samples, ranging from 92 to 570 million years.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] He did not publish these results, which was fortunate because they were flawed by measurement errors and poor estimates of the half-life of radium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood refined his work and finally published the results in 1907.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood's paper pointed out that samples taken from comparable layers of strata had similar lead-to-uranium ratios, and that samples from older layers had a higher proportion of lead, except where there was evidence that lead had leached out of the sample.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] His studies were flawed by the fact that the decay series of thorium was not understood, which led to incorrect results for samples that contained both uranium and thorium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] However, his calculations were far more accurate than any that had been performed to that time.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Refinements in the technique would later give ages for Boltwood's 26 samples of 410 million to 2.2 billion years.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Although Boltwood published his paper in a prominent geological journal, the geological community had little interest in radioactivity.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Boltwood gave up work on radiometric dating and went on to investigate other decay series.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Rutherford remained mildly curious about the issue of the age of Earth but did little work on it.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Robert Strutt tinkered with Rutherford's helium method until 1910 and then ceased.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] However, Strutt's student Arthur Holmes became interested in radiometric dating and continued to work on it after everyone else had given up.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Holmes focused on lead dating because he regarded the helium method as unpromising.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] He performed measurements on rock samples and concluded in 1911 that the oldest (a sample from Ceylon) was about 1.6 billion years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] These calculations were not particularly trustworthy.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] For example, he assumed that the samples had contained only uranium and no lead when they were formed.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] More important research was published in 1913.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] It showed that elements generally exist in multiple variants with different masses, or "isotopes".
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In the 1930s, isotopes would be shown to have nuclei with differing numbers of the neutral particles known as "neutrons".
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] In that same year, other research was published establishing the rules for radioactive decay, allowing more precise identification of decay series.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Many geologists felt these new discoveries made radiometric dating so complicated as to be worthless.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Holmes felt that they gave him tools to improve his techniques, and he plodded ahead with his research, publishing before and after the First World War.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] His work was generally ignored until the 1920s, though in 1917 Joseph Barrell, a professor of geology at Yale, redrew geological history as it was understood at the time to conform to Holmes's findings in radiometric dating.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Barrell's research determined that the layers of strata had not all been laid down at the same rate, and so current rates of geological change could not be used to provide accurate timelines of the history of Earth.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Holmes' persistence finally began to pay off in 1921, when the speakers at the yearly meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science came to a rough consensus that Earth was a few billion years old and that radiometric dating was credible.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Holmes published *The Age of the Earth, an Introduction to Geological Ideas* in 1927 in which he presented a range of 1.6 to 3.0 billion years.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] No great push to embrace radiometric dating followed, however, and the die-hards in the geological community stubbornly resisted.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] They had never cared for attempts by physicists to intrude in their domain, and had successfully ignored them so far.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The growing weight of evidence finally tilted the balance in 1931, when the National Research Council of the US National Academy of Sciences decided to resolve the question of the age of Earth by appointing a committee to investigate.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Holmes, being one of the few people who was trained in radiometric dating techniques, was a committee member and in fact wrote most of the final report.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Thus, Holmes' report concluded that radioactive dating was the only reliable means of pinning down a geologic time scale.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Questions of bias were deflected by the great and exacting detail of the report.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] It described the methods used, the care with which measurements were made, and their error bars and limitations.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Radiometric dating continues to be the predominant way scientists date geologic time scales.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Techniques for radioactive dating have been tested and fine-tuned on an ongoing basis since the 1960s.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Forty or so different dating techniques have been utilized to date, working on a wide variety of materials.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Dates for the same sample using these different techniques are in very close agreement on the age of the material.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Possible contamination problems do exist, but they have been studied and dealt with by careful investigation, leading to sample preparation procedures being minimized to limit the chance of contamination.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] An age of 4.55 ± 0.07 billion years, very close to today's accepted age, was determined by Clair Cameron Patterson using uranium–lead isotope dating (specifically lead–lead dating) on several meteorites including the Canyon Diablo meteorite and published in 1956.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The quoted age of Earth is derived, in part, from the Canyon Diablo meteorite for several important reasons and is built upon a modern understanding of cosmochemistry built up over decades of research.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] To mitigate this effect it is usual to date several minerals in the same sample, to provide an isochron.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Alternatively, more than one dating system may be used on a sample to check the date.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Some meteorites are furthermore considered to represent the primitive material from which the accreting solar disk was formed.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Some have behaved as closed systems (for some isotopic systems) soon after the solar disk and the planets formed.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] To date, these assumptions are supported by much scientific observation and repeated isotopic dates, and it is certainly a more robust hypothesis than that which assumes a terrestrial rock has retained its original composition.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Nevertheless, ancient Archaean lead ores of galena have been used to date the formation of Earth as these represent the earliest formed lead-only minerals on the planet and record the earliest homogeneous lead–lead isotope systems on the planet.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] These have returned age dates of 4.54 billion years with a precision of as little as 1% margin for error.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The Canyon Diablo meteorite was used because it is both large and representative of a particularly rare type of meteorite that contains sulfide minerals (particularly troilite, FeS), metallic nickel-iron alloys, plus silicate minerals.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This is important because the presence of the three mineral phases allows investigation of isotopic dates using samples that provide a great separation in concentrations between parent and daughter nuclides.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This is particularly true of uranium and lead.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Lead is strongly chalcophilic and is found in the sulfide at a much greater concentration than in the silicate, versus uranium.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Because of this segregation in the parent and daughter nuclides during the formation of the meteorite, this allowed a much more precise date of the formation of the solar disk and hence the planets than ever before.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The age determined from the Canyon Diablo meteorite has been confirmed by hundreds of other age determinations, from both terrestrial samples and other meteorites.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The meteorite samples, however, show a spread from 4.53 to 4.58 billion years ago.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This is interpreted as the duration of formation of the solar nebula and its collapse into the solar disk to form the Sun and the planets.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] This 50-million-year time span allows for accretion of the planets from the original solar dust and meteorites.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The Moon, as another extraterrestrial body that has not undergone plate tectonics and that has no atmosphere, provides quite precise age dates from the samples returned from the Apollo missions.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Rocks returned from the Moon have been dated at a maximum of 4.51 billion years old.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Martian meteorites that have landed upon Earth have also been dated to around 4.5 billion years old by lead–lead dating.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Lunar samples, since they have not been disturbed by weathering, plate tectonics or material moved by organisms, can also provide dating by direct electron microscope examination of cosmic ray tracks.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] The accumulation of dislocations generated by high energy cosmic ray particle impacts provides another confirmation of the isotopic dates.
[src:cambrian/age-of-earth] Cosmic ray dating is only useful on material that has not been melted, since melting erases the crystalline structure of the material, and wipes away the tracks left by the particles.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The **Altai-Sayan region** is an area of Inner Asia proximate to the Altai Mountains and the Sayan Mountains, near to where Russia, China, Mongolia and Kazakhstan come together.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] This region is one of the world centers of temperate plant diversity.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Its biological, landscape, historical, cultural and religious diversity is unique.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] 3,726 species of vascular plants are registered in the region including 700 threatened or rare species, 317 of which are endemic; fauna consists of 680 species, 6% of which are endemic.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Its ecosystem is comparatively unchanged since the last ice age, and it is the host of endangered species that include the saiga, nerpa, and snow leopard.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] It is the focus of ongoing international and regional environmental conservation initiatives.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The area is culturally diverse, with four extant language groups (Mongolic, Turkic, Sinitic and Slavic, and formerly Samoyedic and Yeniseian), and more than 20 indigenous ethnic groups practicing traditional land use systems.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] There are also a variety of religions including Christianity, Islam, Buddhism, Tengrism and Shamanism.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The region covers more than one million square kilometers, and has a population of between 5 and 6 million inhabitants.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Altai-Sayan ecoregions contain and share a name with the Altai Mountains and the Sayan Mountains.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Altai Mountains are a mountain range in East-Central Asia, where Russia, China, Mongolia and Kazakhstan come together, and are where the rivers Irtysh and Ob have their headwaters.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Sayan Mountains lie between northwestern Mongolia and southern Siberia.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Altai-Sayan has a total area of 1,065,000 square kilometers.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Its area belongs to the territory of Russia (62%), Mongolia (29%), Kazakhstan (5%) and China (4%).
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] At the far north of the Altai-Sayan region, near its boundary, is the Russian city of Krasnoyarsk (population above 900,000 in 2010 census).
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Other towns in the region include Kyzyl in Russia (pop. about 110,000 in 2008), as well as Ulaangom, Ulgii, and Khovd, all in Mongolia (each with population under 30,000).
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Russian town of Gorno-Altaysk (pop. about 60,000 in 2010) lies within the region near its western boundary, and the Russian city of Irkutsk lies just outside the region to its east.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Altai-Sayan region's total population is estimated as about 5.5 million.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Contained within this ecoregion is the Great Lakes Hollow, a large semi-arid depression, bounded by the Altai in the West, Khangai in the East and Tannu-Ola Mountains in the North.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] This contains six major lakes: the saline lakes Uvs Nuur, Khyargas Nuur and Dörgön Nuur; and freshwater lake Khar-Us Nuur, Khar Nuur and Airag Nuur.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] These are remnants of the West Siberian Glacial Lake, a periglacial lake formed when the Arctic Ocean outlets for each of the Ob and Yenisei rivers were blocked by the Barents-Kara Ice Sheet during the Weichselian Glaciation, approximately 80,000 years ago.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Altai-Sayan is home to the Denisova cave, famous for the 2010 discovery of 50,000-year-old fossils of a new kind of human, the Denisovans.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Since then, Neanderthal bones, and tools crafted by Homo sapiens have been found in the cave.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] This makes it the only place where all three hominins have been known to live.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Conditions in the Altai-Sayan are stable, so ancient humans may have taken refuge there during glacial interchanges and lived off the diverse game species.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Malaya Syya in Khakassia, another ancient archeological site in the region, has been dated to 35,000 BCE.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Recent genetic studies have shown that some indigenous peoples of the Americas are partially derived from southern Altaians.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] According to the *New Scientist*, the mix of mammals in the Altai-Sayan region has been among the least changed since the last ice age, in comparison to the mammalian population of any other region on earth.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Its stability over time suggests that it may have acted as a refugium for mammoth steppe fauna both during and between ice ages.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Great Lakes Hollow, in addition to its saline lakes, contains some of the most important wetlands of Central Asia.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The wetlands are based on the system of interconnected shallow lakes with wide reed belts within the steppe.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The World Wildlife Fund has conducted studies of the region.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] It has identified the Altai-Sayan ecoregion as a priority region for wildlife conservation.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Threats to the biodiversity of the region, according to the Fund, include poaching and illegal wildlife trade, industrial development, climate change, overgrazing and competition for pastures, unsustainable forestry, water pollution, and poverty.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Beginning in the late 1990s, several government-level initiatives were begun with the stated purpose that included helping to preserve the Altai-Sayan ecoregion and biodiversity.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] In 1998, representatives of Kazakhstan, China, Mongolia and Russia met in Urumqi to organize a trans-boundary nature reserve and launch joint biodiversity conservation programs.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] That same year, several republics in the Russian Federation (Tyva, Khakassia and Altai) also signed an environmental protection agreement.
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] However, as of 2010, the steering organization "Altai, Our Common Home" had played a coordinating role "less in conservation and ecological themes" than in "economic and cultural exchange programmes".
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] Analysts stated that "while the [ecosystem conservation] soil has been prepared for cultivation rather well", after 10 years "there are no tangible results yet".
[src:cambrian/altai-sayan-region] The Altai-Sayan region is the northernmost habitat of the snow leopard. a species listed on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species as globally vulnerable.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Altyn Tag means *Gold Mountain* in Turkic, and Jin Shan (金山) is Chinese for *Gold Mountain*.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] A series of mountain ranges run along the northern edge of the Tibetan Plateau, with the Kunlun Mountains located in the West.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] About halfway across the south side of the Tarim Basin, the Altyn-Tagh Range diverges northeast while the Kunluns continue directly east, forming a relatively narrow "V".
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Inside the "V" are a number of endorheic basins.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The eastern end of the Altyn-Shan is near the Dangjin Pass on the Dunhuang-Golmud road in far western Gansu.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] East of the Altyn-Tagh the border range rises to the Qilian Mountains.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The range separates the Tarim Basin, to the north, and Lake Ayakkum, to the south.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The range can be divided into three portions.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The southwest portion borders the Kunlun Mountains and is very rugged, with peaks reaching more than 6,100 metres (20,000 ft) and many perennial snow fields.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The central portion is lower in elevation, around 4,000 metres (13,000 ft).
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The eastern portion is higher in elevation, about 5,000 metres (16,000 ft) and consists of a group of smaller ranges oriented in a south-east to north-west trend.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Along the northern side of the mountains ran the main Silk Road trade route from China proper to the Tarim Basin and westward.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The Altyn-Tagh and Qilians were sometimes called the Nan Shan ('south mountains') because they were south of the main route.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Near the east end of the Altyn-Shan, the Gansu or Hexi Corridor ends and the Silk Road splits.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] One branch follows the Altyn-Tagh along the south side of the Tarim Basin while the other follows the north side.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The southwestern part of the Altyn-Tagh range reaches snowy peaks of up to 6,245 metres (20,489 ft), although it descends to an average of 4,000 metres (13,000 ft) in the narrow middle and eventually rises up to average 5,000 metres (16,000 ft) as it meets the Qilian Mountains.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] There are a dearth of rivers and streams in these mountains, due to the aridity of the region.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The western portion has some small streams that either head north into the desert or south into Lake Ayakkum.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The remainder of the range is lacking in rivers.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Inside the V-shaped area between the Altyn-Tagh and the main Kunlun range (which in this area is called Arka-Tagh) a number of endorheic basins are located.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The two main lakes in this basin are the saline Lake Aqqikkol (also Ajig Kum Kul, Achak-kum; Chinese: 阿其克库勒湖; pinyin: *Āqíkèkùlè Hú*; 37°05′N, 88°25′E, 4,250 metres (13,940 ft) elevation) and Lake Ayakum (Chinese: 阿牙克库木湖; pinyin: *Āyákèkùmù hú*; 37°30′N, 89°30′E; elevation 3,876 metres (12,717 ft)).
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] These lakes are two of the few noticeable bodies of water in this extremely arid area; the area around them is officially protected as the **Altun Shan Nature Reserve**.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] Farther east, in northwestern Qinghai, the much larger Qaidam Basin starts between the Altyn-Tagh and the Kunlun and extends almost to the east side of the plateau; the Altyn-Tagh separates the west side of this basin from the Kumtagh Desert.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] China National Highway 315 crosses the Altyn-Tagh on its way between Qinghai and Xinjiang.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The Golmud-Korla Railway crosses the Altyn-Tagh as well.
[src:cambrian/altyn-tagh] The project, involving the construction of the 13.195 km-long Altyn-Tagh Tunnel (阿尔金山隧道), was completed in 2020.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The **Cambrian** ( /ˈkæmbri.ən, ˈkeɪm-/ *KAM-bree-ən, KAYM-*) is the first geological period of the Paleozoic Era and the Phanerozoic Eon.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Cambrian lasted 51.95 million years from the end of the preceding Ediacaran period 538.8 Ma (million years ago) to the beginning of the Ordovician Period 486.85 Ma.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Most of the continents were located in the southern hemisphere surrounded by the vast Panthalassa Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The assembly of Gondwana during the Ediacaran and early Cambrian led to the development of new convergent plate boundaries and continental-margin arc magmatism along its margins that helped drive up global temperatures.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Laurentia lay across the equator, separated from Gondwana by the opening Iapetus Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Cambrian marked a profound change in life on Earth; prior to the period, the majority of living organisms were small, unicellular, and poorly preserved.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Complex, multicellular organisms gradually became more common during the Ediacaran, but it was not until the Cambrian that fossil diversity seems to have rapidly increased, an event known as the Cambrian explosion, producing the first representatives of most modern animal phyla.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The period is also unique in its unusually high proportion of lagerstätte deposits, sites of exceptional preservation where "soft" parts of organisms are preserved as well as their more resistant shells.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The term *Cambrian* is derived from a Latin version of *Cymru*, the Welsh name for Wales, where rocks of this age were first studied.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The geological term was named by Adam Sedgwick based on work done in the summer of 1831 in North Wales.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Sedgwick divided it into three groups: the Lower, Middle, and Upper Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] He defined the boundary between the Cambrian and the overlying Silurian, together with Roderick Murchison, in their joint paper "*On the Silurian and Cambrian Systems, Exhibiting the Order in which the Older Sedimentary Strata Succeed each other in England and Wales*" (1836).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The proposal to label the period *Cambrian* was based on a segment of rock strata that represented a period of geological time.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Due to the scarcity of fossils, Sedgwick used rock types to identify Cambrian strata.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] He was also slow in publishing further work.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The clear fossil record of the Silurian, however, allowed Murchison to correlate rocks of a similar age across Europe and Russia, and on these he published extensively.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] As increasing numbers of fossils were identified in older rocks, he extended the base of the Silurian downwards into the Sedgwick's "Upper Cambrian", claiming all fossilised strata for "his" Silurian series.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Matters were complicated further when, in 1852, fieldwork carried out by Sedgwick and others revealed an unconformity within the Silurian, with a clear difference in fauna between the two.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This allowed Sedgwick to now claim a large section of the Silurian for "his" Cambrian and gave the Cambrian an identifiable fossil record.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The dispute between the two geologists and their supporters, over the boundary between the Cambrian and Silurian, would extend beyond the life times of both Sedgwick and Murchison.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It was not resolved until 1879, when Charles Lapworth proposed the disputed strata belong to its own system, which he named the Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The term *Cambrian* for the oldest period of the Paleozoic was officially agreed in 1960, at the 21st International Geological Congress.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It only includes Sedgwick's "Lower Cambrian series", but its base has been extended into much older rocks.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Systems, series and stages can be defined globally or regionally.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] For global stratigraphic correlation, the ICS ratify rock units based on a Global Boundary Stratotype Section and Point (GSSP) from a single formation (a stratotype) identifying the lower boundary of the unit.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Currently the boundaries of the Cambrian System, three series and six stages are defined by global stratotype sections and points.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The lower boundary of the Cambrian was originally held to represent the first appearance of complex life, represented by trilobites.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The recognition of small shelly fossils before the first trilobites, and Ediacara biota substantially earlier, has led to calls for a more precisely defined base to the Cambrian Period.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Despite the long recognition of its distinction from younger Ordovician rocks and older Precambrian rocks, it was not until 1994 that the Cambrian system/period was internationally ratified.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] After decades of careful consideration, a continuous sedimentary sequence at Fortune Head, Newfoundland, Canada, was settled upon as a formal base of the Cambrian Period, which was to be correlated worldwide by the earliest appearance of *Treptichnus pedum*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Discovery of this fossil a few metres below the GSSP led to the refinement of this statement, and it is the *T. pedum* ichnofossil assemblage that is now formally used to correlate the base of the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This formal designation allowed radiometric dates to be obtained from samples across the globe that corresponded to the base of the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] An early date of 570 Ma quickly gained favour, though the methods used to obtain this number are now considered to be unsuitable and inaccurate.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] A more precise analysis using modern radiometric dating yields a date of 538.8 ± 0.6 Ma.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The ash horizon in Oman from which this date was recovered corresponds to a marked fall in the abundance of carbon-13 that correlates to equivalent excursions elsewhere in the world, and to the disappearance of distinctive Ediacaran fossils (*Namacalathus*, *Cloudina*).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Nevertheless, there are arguments that the dated horizon in Oman does not correspond to the Ediacaran–Cambrian boundary, but represents a facies change from marine to evaporite-dominated strata – which would mean that dates from other sections, ranging from 544 to 542 Ma, are more suitable.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Terreneuvian is the lowermost series/epoch of the Cambrian, lasting from 538.8 ± 0.6 Ma to c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It is divided into two stages: the Fortunian stage, 538.8 ± 0.6 Ma to c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The name Terreneuvian was ratified by the International Union of Geological Sciences (IUGS) in 2007, replacing the previous "Cambrian Series 1".
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The GSSP defining its base is at Fortune Head on the Burin Peninsula, eastern Newfoundland, Canada (see Ediacaran–Cambrian boundary above).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Terreneuvian is the only series in the Cambrian to contain no trilobite fossils.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its lower part is characterised by complex, sediment-penetrating Phanerozoic-type trace fossils, and its upper part by small shelly fossils.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The second series/epoch of the Cambrian is currently unnamed and known as Cambrian Series 2.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its two stages are also unnamed and known as Cambrian Stage 3, c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The base of Series 2 does not yet have a GSSP, but it is expected to be defined in strata marking the first appearance of trilobites in Gondwana.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] There was a rapid diversification of metazoans during this epoch, but their restricted geographic distribution, particularly of the trilobites and archaeocyaths, have made global correlations difficult, hence ongoing efforts to establish a GSSP.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Miaolingian is the third series/epoch of the Cambrian, lasting from c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 497 Ma, and roughly identical to the middle Cambrian in older literature.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It is divided into three stages: the Wuliuan c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The name replaces Cambrian Series 3 and was ratified by the IUGS in 2018.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It is named after the Miaoling Mountains in southeastern Guizhou Province, South China, where the GSSP marking its base is found.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This is defined by the first appearance of the oryctocephalid trilobite *Oryctocephalus indicus*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The olenellids, eodiscids, and most redlichiids trilobites went extinct at the boundary between Series 2 and the Miaolingian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This is considered the oldest mass extinction of trilobites.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 497 Ma to 486.85 ± 1.5 Ma, is the fourth and uppermost series/epoch of the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The name was ratified by the IUGS in 2003 and replaces Cambrian Series 4 and the traditional "Upper Cambrian".
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The GSSP for the base of the Furongian is in the Wuling Mountains, in northwestern Hunan Province, China.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It coincides with the first appearance of the agnostoid trilobite *Glyptagnostus reticulatus*, and is near the beginning of a large positive δ13C isotopic excursion.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Furongian is divided into three stages: the Paibian, c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 491 Ma, which have defined GSSPs; and the unnamed Cambrian Stage 10, c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The GSSP for the Cambrian–Ordovician boundary is at Green Point, western Newfoundland, Canada, and is dated at 486.85 Ma.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It is defined by the appearance of the conodont *Iapetognathus fluctivagus*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Where these conodonts are not found the appearance of planktonic graptolites or the trilobite *Jujuyaspis borealis* can be used.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The boundary also corresponds with the peak of the largest positive variation in the δ13C curve during the boundary time interval and with a global marine transgression.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Major meteorite impact structures include: the early Cambrian (c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 508 Ma) in Western Australia; the 5 km diameter Mizarai crater (500±10 Ma) in Lithuania; and the 3.2 km diameter Newporte structure (c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 500 Ma or slightly younger) in North Dakota, U.S.A.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Reconstructing the position of the continents during the Cambrian is based on palaeomagnetic, palaeobiogeographic, tectonic, geological and palaeoclimatic data.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, these have different levels of uncertainty and can produce contradictory locations for the major continents.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Most models show Gondwana stretching from the south polar region to north of the equator.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Early in the Cambrian, the south pole corresponded with the western South American sector and as Gondwana rotated anti-clockwise, by the middle of the Cambrian, the south pole lay in the northwest African region.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Laurentia lay across the equator, separated from Gondwana by the Iapetus Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Proponents of Pannotia have Laurentia and Baltica close to the Amazonia region of Gondwana with a narrow Iapetus Ocean that only began to open once Gondwana was fully assembled c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Those not in favour of the existence of Pannotia show the Iapetus opening during the Late Neoproterozoic, with up to c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 4038 miles) between Laurentia and West Gondwana at the beginning of the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Of the smaller continents, Baltica lay between Laurentia and Gondwana, the Ran Ocean (an arm of the Iapetus) opening between it and Gondwana.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Siberia lay close to the western margin of Gondwana and to the north of Baltica.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Annamia and South China formed a single continent situated off north central Gondwana.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It may have lain along the northeast Indian sector of Gondwana or already have been a separate continent.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the Cambrian, Laurentia lay across or close to the equator.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 20° anticlockwise during the middle Cambrian, before drifting north again in the late Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] After the Late Neoproterozoic (or mid-Cambrian) rifting of Laurentia from Gondwana and the subsequent opening of the Iapetus Ocean, Laurentia was largely surrounded by passive margins with much of the continent covered by shallow seas.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] As Laurentia separated from Gondwana, a sliver of continental terrane rifted from Laurentia with the narrow Taconic seaway opening between them.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The remains of this terrane are now found in southern Scotland, Ireland, and Newfoundland.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Intra-oceanic subduction either to the southeast of this terrane in the Iapetus, or to its northwest in the Taconic seaway, resulted in the formation of an island arc.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This accreted to the terrane in the late Cambrian, triggering southeast-dipping subduction beneath the terrane itself and consequent closure of the marginal seaway.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The terrane collided with Laurentia in the Early Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Towards the end of the early Cambrian, rifting along Laurentia's southeastern margin led to the separation of Cuyania (now part of Argentina) from the Ouachita embayment with a new ocean established that continued to widen through the Cambrian and Early Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Gondwana was a massive continent, three times the size of any of the other Cambrian continents.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its continental land area extended from the south pole to north of the equator.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Around it were extensive shallow seas and numerous smaller land areas.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The cratons that formed Gondwana came together during the Neoproterozoic to early Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] A narrow ocean separated Amazonia from Gondwana until c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 530 Ma and the Arequipa-Antofalla block united with the South American sector of Gondwana in the early Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Kuunga Orogeny between northern (Congo Craton, Madagascar and India) and southern Gondwana (Kalahari Craton and East Antarctica), which began c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 570 Ma, continued with parts of northern Gondwana over-riding southern Gondwana and was accompanied by metamorphism and the intrusion of granites.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Subduction zones, active since the Neoproterozoic, extended around much of Gondwana's margins, from northwest Africa southwards round South America, South Africa, East Antarctica, and the eastern edge of West Australia.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Shorter subduction zones existed north of Arabia and India.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Famatinian continental arc stretched from central Peru in the north to central Argentina in the south.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Subduction beneath this proto-Andean margin began by the late Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Along the northern margin of Gondwana, between northern Africa and the Armorican Terranes of southern Europe, the continental arc of the Cadomian Orogeny continued from the Neoproterozoic in response to the oblique subduction of the Iapetus Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This subduction extended west along the Gondwanan margin and by c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 530 Ma may have evolved into a major transform fault system.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 511 Ma the continental flood basalts of the Kalkarindji large igneous province (LIP) began to erupt.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These covered an area of > 2.1 million km2 across northern, central and Western Australia regions of Gondwana making it one of the largest, as well as the earliest, LIPs of the Phanerozoic.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The timing of the eruptions suggests they played a role in the early to middle Cambrian mass extinction.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The terranes of Ganderia, East and West Avalonia, Carolinia and Meguma lay in polar regions during the early Cambrian, and high-to-mid southern latitudes by the mid to late Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] They are commonly shown as an island arc-transform fault system along the northwestern margin of Gondwana north of northwest Africa and Amazonia, which rifted from Gondwana during the Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, some models show these terranes as part of a single independent microcontinent, Greater Avalonia, lying to the west of Baltica and aligned with its eastern (Timanide) margin, with the Iapetus to the north and the Ran Ocean to the south.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the Cambrian, Baltica rotated more than 60° anti-clockwise and began to drift northwards.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This rotation was accommodated by major strike-slip movements in the Ran Ocean between it and Gondwana.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Baltica lay at mid-to-high southerly latitudes, separated from Laurentia by the Iapetus and from Gondwana by the Ran Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It was composed of two continents, Fennoscandia and Sarmatia, separated by shallow seas.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The sediments deposited in these unconformably overlay Precambrian basement rocks.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The lack of coarse-grained sediments indicates low lying topography across the centre of the craton.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Along Baltica's northeastern margin subduction and arc magmatism associated with the Ediacaran Timanian Orogeny was coming to an end.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] In this region the early to middle Cambrian was a time of non-deposition and followed by late Cambrian rifting and sedimentation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its southeastern margin was also a convergent boundary, with the accretion of island arcs and microcontinents to the craton, although the details are unclear.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Siberia began the Cambrian close to western Gondwana and north of Baltica.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It drifted northwestwards to close to the equator as the Ægir Ocean opened between it and Baltica.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Much of the continent was covered by shallow seas with extensive archaeocyathan reefs.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The then northern third of the continent (present day south; Siberia has rotated 180° since the Cambrian) adjacent to its convergent margin was mountainous.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] From the Late Neoproterozoic to the Ordovician, a series of island arcs accreted to Siberia's then northeastern margin, accompanied by extensive arc and back-arc volcanism.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These now form the Altai-Sayan terranes.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Some models show a convergent plate margin extending from Greater Avalonia, through the Timanide margin of Baltica, forming the Kipchak island arc offshore of southeastern Siberia and curving round to become part of the Altai-Sayan convergent margin.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Along the then western margin, Late Neoproterozoic to early Cambrian rifting was followed by the development of a passive margin.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] To the then north, Siberia was separated from the Central Mongolian terrane by the narrow and slowly opening Mongol-Okhotsk Ocean.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Central Mongolian terrane's northern margin with the Panthalassa was convergent, whilst its southern margin facing the Mongol-Okhotsk Ocean was passive.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the Cambrian, the terranes that would form Kazakhstania later in the Paleozoic were a series of island arc and accretionary complexes that lay along an intra-oceanic convergent plate margin to the south of North China.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] To the south of these the Tarim microcontinent lay between Gondwana and Siberia.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its northern margin was passive for much of the Paleozoic, with thick sequences of platform carbonates and fluvial to marine sediments resting unconformably on Precambrian basement.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Along its southeast margin was the Altyn Cambro–Ordovician accretionary complex, whilst to the southwest a subduction zone was closing the narrow seaway between the North West Kunlun region of Tarim and the South West Kunlun terrane.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] North China lay at equatorial to tropical latitudes during the early Cambrian, although its exact position is unknown.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Some models show that it lies below the equatorial latitudes.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Much of the craton was covered by shallow seas, with land in the northwest and southeast.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Northern North China was a passive margin until the onset of subduction and the development of the Bainaimiao arc in the late Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] To its south was a convergent margin with a southwest dipping subduction zone, beyond which lay the North Qinling terrane (now part of the Qinling Orogenic Belt), together with Qilian-Qaidam, Altyn belts, and South West Kunlun terranes.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] South China and Annamia formed a single continent.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Strike-slip movement between it and Gondwana accommodated its steady drift northwards from offshore the Indian sector of Gondwana to near the western Australian sector.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This northward drift is evidenced by the progressive increase in limestones and increasing faunal diversity.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The northern margin South China, including the South Qinling block, was a passive margin.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Along the southeastern margin, lower Cambrian volcanics indicate the accretion of an island arc along the Song Ma suture zone.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Also, early in the Cambrian, the eastern margin of South China changed from passive to active, with the development of oceanic volcanic island arcs that now form part of the Japanese terrane.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The distribution of climate-indicating sediments, including the wide latitudinal distribution of tropical carbonate platforms, archaeocyathan reefs and bauxites, and arid zone evaporites and calcrete deposits, show the Cambrian was a time of greenhouse climate conditions.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the late Cambrian the distribution of trilobite provinces also indicate only a moderate pole-to-equator temperature gradient.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] There is evidence of glaciation at high latitudes on Avalonia.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, it is unclear whether these sediments are early Cambrian or actually late Neoproterozoic in age.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Calculations of global average temperatures (GAT) vary depending on which techniques are used.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Whilst some measurements show GAT over c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 40 °C (104 °F) models that combine multiple sources give GAT of c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 20–22 °C (68–72 °F) in the Terreneuvian increasing to c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The warm climate was linked to elevated atmospheric carbon dioxide levels.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Assembly of Gondwana led to the reorganisation of the tectonic plates with the development of new convergent plate margins and continental-margin arc magmatism that helped drive climatic warming.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The eruptions of the Kalkarindji LIP basalts during Stage 4 and into the early Miaolingian, also released large quantities of carbon dioxide, methane and sulphur dioxide into the atmosphere leading to rapid climatic changes and elevated sea surface temperatures.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] There is uncertainty around the maximum sea surface temperatures.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These are calculated using δ18O values from marine rocks, and there is an ongoing debate about the levels δ18O in Cambrian seawater relative to the rest of the Phanerozoic.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Estimates for tropical sea surface temperatures vary from c.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Modern average tropical sea surface temperatures are 26 °C (79 °F).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Atmospheric oxygen levels rose steadily rising from the Neoproterozoic due to the increase in photosynthesising organisms.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Low levels of atmospheric oxygen and the warm climate resulted in lower dissolved oxygen concentrations in marine waters and widespread anoxia in deep ocean waters.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] There is a complex relationship between oxygen levels, the biogeochemistry of ocean waters, and the evolution of life.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Newly evolved burrowing organisms exposed anoxic sediments to the overlying oxygenated seawater.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This bioturbation decreased the burial rates of organic carbon and sulphur, which over time reduced atmospheric and oceanic oxygen levels, leading to widespread anoxic conditions.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Periods of higher rates of continental weathering led to increased delivery of nutrients to the oceans, boosting productivity of phytoplankton and stimulating metazoan evolution.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, rapid increases in nutrient supply led to eutrophication, where rapid growth in phytoplankton numbers result in the depletion of oxygen in the surrounding waters.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Pulses of increased oxygen levels are linked to increased biodiversity; raised oxygen levels supported the increasing metabolic demands of organisms, and increased ecological niches by expanding habitable areas of seafloor.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Overall, these dynamic, fluctuating environments, with global and regional anoxic incursions resulting in extinction events, and periods of increased oceanic oxygenation stimulating biodiversity, drove evolutionary innovation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the Cambrian, variations in isotope ratios were more frequent and more pronounced than later in the Phanerozoic, with at least 10 carbon isotope (δ13C) excursions (significant variations in global isotope ratios) recognised.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The basal Cambrian δ13C excursion (BACE), together with low δ238U and raised δ34S indicates a period of widespread shallow marine anoxia, which occurs at the same time as the extinction of the Ediacaran acritarchs.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] It was followed by the rapid appearance and diversification of bilaterian animals.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the early Cambrian, 87Sr/86Sr rose in response to enhanced continental weathering.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This increased the input of nutrients into the oceans and led to higher burial rates of organic matter.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Over long timescales, the extra oxygen released by organic carbon burial is balanced by a decrease in the rates of pyrite (FeS2) burial (a process which also releases oxygen), leading to stable levels of oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, during the early Cambrian, a series of linked δ13C and δ34S excursions indicate high burial rates of both organic carbon and pyrite in biologically productive yet anoxic ocean floor waters.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The oxygen-rich waters produced by these processes spread from the deep ocean into shallow marine environments, extending the habitable regions of the seafloor.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These pulses of oxygen are associated with the radiation of the small shelly fossils and the Cambrian arthropod radiation isotope excursion (CARE).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The increase in oxygenated waters in the deep ocean ultimately reduced the levels of organic carbon and pyrite burial, leading to a decrease in oxygen production and the re-establishment of anoxic conditions.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This cycle was repeated several times during the early Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The beginning of the eruptions of the Kalkarindji LIP basalts during Stage 4 and the early Miaolingian released large quantities of carbon dioxide, methane and sulphur dioxide into the atmosphere.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The changes these wrought are reflected by three large and rapid δ13C excursions.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Increased temperatures led to a global sea level rise that flooded continental shelves and interiors with anoxic waters from the deeper ocean and drowned carbonate platforms of archaeocyathan reefs, resulting in the widespread accumulation of black organic-rich shales.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Known as the Sinsk anoxic extinction event, this triggered the first major extinction of the Phanerozoic, the 513–508 Ma Botomian–Toyonian Extinction (BTE), which included the loss of the archaeocyathids and hyoliths and saw a major drop in biodiversity.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The rise in sea levels is also evidenced by a global decrease in 87Sr/86Sr.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The flooding of continental areas decreased the rates of continental weathering, reducing the input of 87Sr to the oceans and lowering the 87Sr/86Sr of seawater.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The base of the Miaolingian is marked by the Redlichiid–Olenellid extinction carbon isotope event (ROECE), which coincides with the main phase of Kalkarindji volcanism.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the Miaolingian, orogenic events along the Australian–Antarctic margin of Gondwana led to an increase in weathering and an influx of nutrients into the ocean, raising the level of productivity and organic carbon burial.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These can be seen in the steady increase in 87Sr/86Sr and δ13C.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Continued erosion of the deeper levels of the Gondwanan mountain belts led to a peak in 87Sr/86Sr and linked positive δ13C and δ34S excursions, known as the Steptoean positive carbon isotope excursion (SPICE).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This indicates similar geochemical conditions to Stages 2 and 3 of the early Cambrian existed, with the expansion of seafloor anoxia enhancing the burial rates of organic matter and pyrite.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This increase in the extent of anoxic seafloor conditions led to the extinction of the marjumiid and damesellid trilobites, whilst the increase in oxygen levels that followed helped drive the radiation of plankton.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 87Sr/86Sr fell sharply near the top of the Jiangshanian Stage, and through Stage 10 as the Gondwanan mountains were eroded down and rates of weathering decreased.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The mineralogy of inorganic marine carbonates has varied through the Phanerozoic, controlled by the Mg2+/Ca2+ values of seawater.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] High Mg2+/Ca2+ result in calcium carbonate precipitation dominated by aragonite and high-magnesium calcite, known as aragonite seas, and low ratios result in calcite seas where low-magnesium calcite is the primary calcium carbonate precipitate.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The shells and skeletons of biomineralising organisms reflect the dominant form of calcite.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] During the late Ediacaran to early Cambrian increasing oxygen levels led to a decrease in ocean acidity and an increase in the concentration of calcium in sea water.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, there was not a simple transition from aragonite to calcite seas, rather a protracted and variable change through the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Aragonite and high-magnesium precipitation continued from the Ediacaran into Cambrian Stage 2.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Low-magnesium calcite skeletal hard parts appear in Cambrian Age 2, but inorganic precipitation of aragonite also occurred at this time.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Mixed aragonite–calcite seas continued through the middle and late Cambrian, with fully calcite seas not established until the early Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These variations and slow decrease in Mg2+/Ca2+ of seawater were due to low oxygen levels, high continental weathering rates and the geochemistry of the Cambrian seas.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] In conditions of low oxygen and high iron levels, iron substitutes for magnesium in authigenic clay minerals deposited on the ocean floor, slowing the removal rates of magnesium from seawater.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The enrichment of ocean waters in silica, prior to the radiation of siliceous organisms, and the limited bioturbation of the anoxic ocean floor increased the rates of deposition, relative to the rest of the Phanerozoic, of these clays.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This, together with the high input of magnesium into the oceans via enhanced continental weathering, delayed the reduction in Mg2+/Ca2+ and facilitated continued aragonite precipitation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The conditions that favoured the deposition of authigenic clays were also ideal for the formation of *lagerstätten*, with the minerals in the clays replacing the soft body parts of Cambrian organisms.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Cambrian flora was little different from the Ediacaran.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The principal taxa were the marine macroalgae *Fuxianospira*, *Sinocylindra*, and *Marpolia*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] No calcareous macroalgae are known from the period.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] No land plant (embryophyte) fossils are known from the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, biofilms and microbial mats were well developed on Cambrian tidal flats and beaches 500 mya, and microbes forming microbial Earth ecosystems, comparable with modern soil crust of desert regions, contributing to soil formation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Although molecular clock estimates suggest terrestrial plants may have first emerged during the Middle or Late Cambrian, the consequent large-scale removal of the greenhouse gas CO2 from the atmosphere through sequestration did not begin until the Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Land plants may have emerged during the Cambrian, but the evidence for this is fragmentary and contested and the oldest unamibiguous evidence for land plants is from the following Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Molecular clock estimates have also led some authors to suggest that arthropods colonised land during the Cambrian, but again the earliest physical evidence of this is during the following Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Cambrian explosion was a period of rapid multicellular growth.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Most animal life during the Cambrian was aquatic.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Trilobites were once assumed to be the dominant life form at that time, but this has proven to be incorrect.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Arthropods were by far the most dominant animals in the ocean, but trilobites were only a minor part of the total arthropod diversity.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] What made them so apparently abundant was their heavy armor reinforced by calcium carbonate (CaCO3), which fossilized far more easily than the fragile chitinous exoskeletons of other arthropods, leaving numerous preserved remains.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The period marked a steep change in the diversity and composition of Earth's biosphere.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Ediacaran biota suffered a mass extinction at the start of the Cambrian Period, which corresponded with an increase in the abundance and complexity of burrowing behaviour.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] This behaviour had a profound and irreversible effect on the substrate which transformed the seabed ecosystems.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Before the Cambrian, the sea floor was covered by microbial mats.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] By the end of the Cambrian, burrowing animals had destroyed the mats in many areas through bioturbation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] As a consequence, many of those organisms that were dependent on the mats became extinct, while the other species adapted to the changed environment that now offered new ecological niches.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Around the same time there was a seemingly rapid appearance of representatives of all the mineralized phyla, including the Bryozoa, which were once thought to have only appeared in the Lower Ordovician.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] However, many of those phyla were represented only by stem-group forms; and since mineralized phyla generally have a benthic origin, they may not be a good proxy for (more abundant) non-mineralized phyla.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] While the early Cambrian showed such diversification that it has been named the Cambrian Explosion, this changed later in the period, when there occurred a sharp drop in biodiversity.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] About 515 Ma, the number of species going extinct exceeded the number of new species appearing.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Five million years later, the number of genera had dropped from an earlier peak of about 600 to just 450.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Also, the speciation rate in many groups was reduced to between a fifth and a third of previous levels.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Marine life lived under low and fluctuating levels of oxygen where upwellings of anoxic deep ocean waters into shallow marine environments could push organisms over the edge into mass extinctions.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Ultimately, however, these led to increased biodiversity as new ecological niches became available.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Some Cambrian organisms ventured onto land, producing the trace fossils *Protichnites* and *Climactichnites*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Fossil evidence suggests that euthycarcinoids, an extinct group of arthropods, produced at least some of the *Protichnites*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Fossils of the track-maker of *Climactichnites* have not been found; however, fossil trackways and resting traces suggest a large, slug-like mollusc.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Porifera (sponges), Cnidaria (e.g. jellyfish, Hydrozoa, sea anemones and corals) and Ctenophora (comb jellies) have an uneven fossil record in the Cambrian and are best preserved in Lagerstätten.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Their evolutionary relationships are the subject of ongoing debate.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Prior to about 513 Ma both stem and crown groups were present, however, many stem groups went extinct during the Sinsk anoxic event at the end of Series 2, with crown groups diversifying afterwards.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Porifera are divided into three main groups: Calcarea (calcareous sponges), Hexactinellida (silica or glass sponges), and Demospongia (spongin and/or silica sponges).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Demospongia are most common in the Cambrian fossil record, Hexactiniellida and Calcarea may be present but the evidence is contested, as is evidence of Ediacaran sponges.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Reticulosa, Heteractinida and Protomonaxonida) are considered stem-groups of these major sponge lineages as they have sponge-like features, but the groups themselves are extinct.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] For example, *Eiffelia* (a heteractinid) has features of calcareous and siliceous sponges with spicules of both silica and calcium carbonate.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Archaeocyatha are probably related to demosponges.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] They first appear in the fossil record in Stage 2 of the Terreneuvian, rapidly diversifying during Stage 3 of Series 2, before going into a sharp decline during Stage 4 and going extinct during the Sinsk anoxic event.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Archaeocyatha were sessile, suspension feeders that pumped water through their porous cup-shaped calcareous skeletons.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Together with cyanobacteria, they were the primary reef builders in the early Cambrian, constructing the oldest known large-scale structures built by animals.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The presence of cyanobacteria within the skeletal framework of Archaeocyatha suggests a photosymbiotic relationship.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Cyanobacteria and other calcimicrobes precipitated calcium carbonate, which encrusted Archaeocyatha skeletons, binding them together to form the framework of the reef.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Early coral-like anthozoans (cnidarians) also contributed to reef building.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These died out together with Archaeocyatha during the Sinsk anoxic event.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] They were replaced by lithistid demosponges as the principal reef building sponges for the rest of the Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Ctenophora (comb jellies) are a group of pelagic, predatory animals with gelatinous, globular bodies, and comb rows (external cilia) which are used for propulsion.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The oldest undisputed ctenophore fossils are found in the lower Cambrian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Cambrian ctenophores had more comb rows, but lack paired tentacles with colloblasts, which modern ctenophores use for feeding.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Stem group Ctenophora include Scleroctenophora, which had paired comb rows, and organic skeleton something modern ctenophores lack.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Dinomischids were polyp-like, sessile filter feeders with organic skeletons that collected food via a crown of tentacles around their mouths.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These have been assigned to both Ctenophora with the suggestion the tentacles evolved into comb rows, and Cnidaria because the internal structures more closely resemble those of a sea anemone-like ancestor.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Cnidarians are divided into two main classes; Anthozoa (sea anemones, corals), which are benthic polyps, and Medusozoa (hydroids, jellyfishes), which have alternating life cycle stages of polyps and medusae (free swimming).
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The oldest example of a jellyfish in the fossil record is *Olivooides* an embryonic jellyfish from the Fortunian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Examples of anthozoans are found from Series 2.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] One of these, the polyp-like *Nailiana elegans* was a stem-group anthozoan.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Its long, flexible tentacles were used to detect, grasp, and drag prey into its mouth in a similar manner to modern predatory sea anemones.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] 520 Ma) shows the earliest known evidence of this macrophagous style of predation.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The fossil preserves a brachiopod surrounded by the *N. elegans*' tentacles with part of the brachiopod already within the cnidarian.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] Many modes of preservation are unique to the Cambrian, and some preserve soft body parts, resulting in an abundance of *Lagerstätten*.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] These include Sirius Passet, the Sinsk Algal Lens, the Maotianshan Shales, the Emu Bay Shale, and the Burgess Shale.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The United States Federal Geographic Data Committee uses a "barred capital C" ⟨Ꞓ⟩ character to represent the Cambrian Period.
[src:cambrian/cambrian] The Unicode character is U+A792 Ꞓ LATIN CAPITAL LETTER C WITH BAR.
